**11. Implications for NoUI Development**

**11.1 Market Positioning**

NoUI addresses critical industry needs:

\- Legacy system modernization without full replacement

\- Rules derivation from governing documents (not legacy behavior)

\- Transparent, auditable calculations required for fiduciary compliance

\- Middleware approach reduces risk compared to system replacement

**11.2 Key Differentiators**

\- AI assists configuration but never executes business rules

\- Calculations verifiable to the penny against hand calculations

\- Progressive schema mapping grows with deployment scope

\- Multi-tier benefit structures handled through rules engine

**11.3 Trust Building**

Industry context emphasizes need for trust:

\- Pension boards have been burned by technology vendors

\- Fiduciary obligations require deterministic, auditable systems

\- Tiered access model (offline analysis → read-only → transactional)
builds confidence

\- Show work transparency addresses regulatory scrutiny

**11.4 Technical Considerations**

Research confirms NoUI technical approach:

\- Legacy systems often lack modern APIs (Data Connector value
proposition)

\- Cloud-native architecture aligns with industry direction (60%+ cloud
adoption)

\- Schema Intelligence addresses data quality challenges

\- Self-service portal expectations align with Dynamic Workspace concept

**11.5 Sales and Implementation Priorities**

Prioritize demonstrating:

\- Calculation accuracy and transparency

\- Rules traceability to governing documents

\- Data quality discovery capabilities

\- Minimal disruption to current operations

\- Compliance with GASB and actuarial requirements
